<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41786163</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>24</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>24</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1879-0003</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>353</Volume><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Apr</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>International journal of biological macromolecules</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Int J Biol Macromol</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Synthesis of Limonia acidissima gum-based biopolymer/samarium substituted hydroxyapatite biocomposite for bone tissue engineering applications.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>151148</StartPage><MedlinePgn>151148</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.ijbiomac.2026.151148</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S0141-8130(26)01074-3</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>Valorization of marine waste into nanostructured biomaterials offers a cost-effective and ecofriendly strategy for bone tissue engineering applications. Here, we report that the Limonia acidissima gum (LAG)-assisted biotemplating approach was employed to synthesise rod shaped samarium substituted hydroxyapatite (SmHAp) biocomposite. LAG is a natural phytopolymer that acted as a green structure directing and stabilizing agent, whereas Sm substitution improved lattice stability, osteogenic potential and antibacterial activity. Biocomposites were fabricated with three LAG concentrations of 0.5, 2, 5&#xa0;wt% and systematically characterised for their physicochemical, functional and biological properties. The LAG-SmHAp biocomposite exhibited 52% swelling and 36% degradation over 14&#xa0;days in PBS. In vitro bioactivity of the biocomposite immersed in SBF confirmed apatite layer formation after 7 and 14&#xa0;days. The biocomposite exhibited significant antibacterial activity at 50 and 100&#xa0;&#x3bc;g/mL that shows concentration dependent inhibition against Escherichia coli and Staphylococcus aureus with the maximum inhibition zone of 18 and 19&#xa0;mm at 100&#xa0;&#x3bc;g/mL. Biocompatibility assessment of the synthesised biocomposite on L929 cells indicated non-toxicity, with an IC&#x2085;&#x2080; value of 99.30&#xa0;&#x3bc;g/mL. In contrast, MG-63 osteosarcoma cells exhibited dose-dependent inhibition of proliferation when treated with the biocomposite at concentrations ranging from 12.5 to 200&#xa0;&#x3bc;g/mL. Alizarin Red S staining performed on HAp, SmHAp, 0.5, 2, 5&#xa0;wt% LAG-SmHAp biocomposites at 5 and 10&#xa0;days confirmed a marked increase in calcium deposition and mineralization. In conclusion, the LAG-assisted SmHAp biocomposite emerges as a sustainable, multifunctional biomaterial well suited for bone tissue engineering applications.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2026 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Kaveri</LastName><ForeName>Merina</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Chemistry, Periyar University, Salem, 636 011, Tamilnadu, India.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Shajahaan</LastName><ForeName>Shake Abbas</ForeName><Initials>SA</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Chemistry, Periyar University, Salem, 636 011, Tamilnadu, India.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Dhanaraj</LastName><ForeName>Gopi</ForeName><Initials>G</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Chemistry, Periyar University, Salem, 636 011, Tamilnadu, India. Electronic address: dhanaraj_gopi@yahoo.com.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType>